snippet.title: Talk To Text
snippet.description: Knowing now that he would have to keep this charade up if it meant staying in a rent-controlled apartment, Joey went on to marry Tim, have five children by his name, move out of the rent-controlled apartment to a nice house in the suburbs, lobby for a raise at work, use the extra money to surprise Tim with a $5,000 investment on his dream of selling jars of honey, take a second honeymoon in the Maldives, go to their sons' Pop Warner games together, take their oldest daughter around the country to look at colleges in a big loving road trip, eventually sell the house for a quaint one-story in their old age, hold their first grandchildren together, ride a ferry out to see the Statue of Liberty like they always said they would do, hold hands as the 4th of July fireworks popped and crackled above, say goodbye to him on the hospital bed, then soon lose grip on living himself in the lonely weeks to come. Just so as not to risk confrontation.

snippet.title: The Man
snippet.description: Stan Lee's entire workday is like this. Just endlessly holding court for random twenty- and thirty-somethings, most of whom have nothing to offer the world, others who only have things to take from it. He even has it pencilled into his daily schedule: Deal With Idiot Youngsters, 9:30A - 4:45P. How he has time to cameo in all those Marvel movies, nobody knows.

snippet.title: Welcome to Chincón
snippet.description: Officer Sminkle was a man on the run. A lone gun, wanted for the murder of America's bird. A private eye hiding behind a faded badge in the most dangerous town in Mexico - but that didn't stop him from trying to make tourist videos for a few pesos on the side. He could have lived out his life in hiding here, sipping down horchatas and looking over his shoulder every bullet-riddled block. But fate had different designs for the Smink.

snippet.title: Stepfather's Christmas
snippet.description: It had been hard for him to win their love. They were finicky, standoffish and distrustful of him, as stepchildren are often wont to be. But he had one last ace up his sleeve: Two tickets to ride on the coal train at his work, deep into the center of Tristeza Negra Mine, where they'd pop a tent and spend some quality family time together by camping. You know what they say: The quickest way to a child's heart is through their lungs.

snippet.title: Santa Lays Some Hard Truth
snippet.description: It's not that Santa's job requires him to keep tabs on kids once they grow out of believing in him, and believing that unprotected sex is gross and filled with cooties. It's just that he can't stop knowing. Ever had a light switch you can't turn off? Now put that light switch in your brain and fill it with images of visits to the free clinic.

snippet.title: Rad Dudes (feat. Freddie Wong)
snippet.description: The radness of these dudes was truly legendary. Tales of their rude 'tudes spread far and wide, echoing off every majestic mountaintop, milliseconds before those mountaintops exploded into brilliant fireballs of rock and roll. Wild falcons cawed in time with their mighty heartbeats. A thunderstorm of Clydesdale hooves signaled their every arrival. With but one rapacious wink of their piercing eyes, any radical babe perched on the hood of a Corvette was theirs, heart body and soul. Indeed, their sickness was too unfathomably grand for this world, which explains the whole them-exploding-instead-of-the-car-they-planted-a-bomb-in thing.

snippet.title: Fugitive Penguin
snippet.description:
He's spent his whole life on the waddle from the cops. An innocent penguin, framed for a crime he didn't commit, forced to slide from town to town and lay low on his belly. The cops, inevitably, always find him holed up at some dingy motel near a large body of water, and by the time they tell him to freeze, it's too late. Gone like a shot.

He's a penguin, baby. Freezing is what he does best.

snippet.title: Wardrobe Malfunction
snippet.description: Larry had a long day. He interviewed a bunch of idiots, had a sandwich, talked to a giant bagel, and had to arrange for special transportation so the bagel wouldn't get eaten by seagulls on its way to the bus depot. He was exhausted, and could think of no better place to take a load off than his trusty interviewing chair. Yes, this would be the premium location for tranquility and thoughtful reflection...perhaps, even, for pondering what sandwich he would eat next. But Michael Rousselet was still there, sitting, waiting for him as if no one told him to leave. Maybe those people did leave, and Michael didn't listen. Maybe he buried them under the floorboards in the green room. Either way, Larry wanted to sit down.

snippet.title: Monticello
snippet.description: Jefferson showed his drawings to Washington, who branded them "juvenile," "tasteless" and "not what this country needs right now." Then he went and stole the concept entirely for his own monument. George Washington: History's biggest dickhead.

snippet.title: Guns
snippet.description: This incident spawned a massive gun control debate that raged its way into the media and Congress. Sweeping legislation was passed that effectively shuttered all gyms, outlawed protein powder and allowed police to arrest anyone deemed a Buff Hazard on sight. Those who protested were shot on sight, because they were flexing too hard while holding their protest signs aloft.

snippet.title: The Great Bagel Debate
snippet.description:
Larry continued to eat his sandwich from last Friday's 5-Second Film, "5SF: The Interview." He munched on it, savoring every bite, and washed it all down with a piping hot mug of cocoa. This was truly the best sandwich he ever had, even if the flavor profile was heightened psychologically by no longer having to interview those idiots at 5-Second Films, which unfortunately was preserved in digital form forever on his Hulu show Larry King Now so that anyone could see it. Finally, he was down to his last savory bite, a mouth-watering blend of mayonnaise, mustard, oven-roasted turkey breast, freshly-baked ciabatta bread, crisp lettuce and ripe juicy tomato slices. He was satiated, and at peace with the universe. It was time to interview a giant talking bagel.

snippet.title: Girl Back Home
snippet.description: It's the first rule of warfare: Never show your fellow trenchmate a photo of who you're fighting this godforsaken war for back home. Wait, no, I got that wrong. That's the second rule. The actual first rule is don't take a picture of who you're fighting this godforsaken war for at a low angle, or with bad lighting that makes the neck look weird, or when they just had dairy. The third rule is don't die, but that sort of goes without saying.

snippet.title: 5SF: The Interview
snippet.description:
Larry's next three cards said "No really, I have a show to run, please stop talking," "So this is why you guys aren't more successful," and "I'm hungry. I should get up and leave." He got up and left, had a sandwich, and wondered who the heck wrote those cards out and, if they had a time machine, maybe they could take him back to before he agreed to do this interview. Then he finished his sandwich.

snippet.title: Hungry Hungry Hungry Hungry Hippos
snippet.description: On the day of the last white pellet, Yellow Hippo pulled out his harmonica and trilled a little ditty. It wafted into the boxy night sky, aided only by the small crackling fire that Blue Hippo started for warmth. They shared stories of games past, when life was but a larkish competition. Green Hippo laughed grimly, a small glimmer of hope flickering as fast and intangibly as the billowing flame before them. Then the true Hungry Hungry Hunger set in.
